{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_havarti_ver01/data/sn83045293/00542868995/1927051201/0560.xml":{"full_text":"BANK TRANSACTIONS\nWednesday, May 11, 1927\n$22,705,516\nAll banks reported.\nSteel Production and Sales Show Decline During April\nMILLS CUT TO\n75 PER CENT\nOF CAPACITY\nPrices No Lower\nThan Former\nFigures.\nThe output and sales .of steel\nghow a diminishing tendency, the\nweekly trade reviews report.\nApril Ingot production dropped 5\nper cent from March, but it did\nsoar to a new pinnacle for April,\naccording to The Iron Trade Re\nview. The month\u2019s total of 4,129,-\n052 gross tons compares with 4,534,-\n926 tons in March, the all time high,\nand 4,105,799 tons last April, that\nmedium states. Production of steel\ningots during the month averaged\n158,844 tons a day, according to\nIron Age. The first four months\u2019\noutput is practically equal to the\nrecord breaking volume of the first\nthird of 1926. Unfilled orders of\nthe United States Steel corporation\non April 30 were smaller than at\nany time in 32 months.\nMills at 75 Per Cent.\n\u201cSo far this month new orders\nand specifications together call for\nabout as much rolled steel as in the\nfirst 10 days of April, but mills are\nfor adjusting operations to an ex\npected reduced demand paralleling\nthe trend last year, in which July\nwas the low point,\u2019\u2019 asserts Iron\nAge. \u201cLacking many large single\npurchases, the market appears\nquiet, but this comes in part from\ncomparison with its busiest peri\nods\u201d\nOperations in the Pittsburgh and\nnearby districts are put at 75 per\ncent capacity, against 80 per cent\ntwo weeks ago.\nPrice Held Steady.\n\u201cPrices are no lower than they\nhave been. The recent rise in sheet\nquotations has driven in a fair\nvolume of business and much of\nthis at advances of $1 and $2 a ton\nand some even at the levels obtain\ning in December. The firmness\nagainst concessions points to a test\ncoming before the month is out,\nwhen renewed buying becomes nec\nessary, Iron Age goes on. \u201cThe\nfacts are Interpreted as establish\ning the Increasingly close ordering\nfor needs. A survey of consuming\nindustries points to no rapid change\nin the largo diversified consump\ntion shown by the statistics of ship\nments.\u201d\nChicago Cash Grain\n1.45; No. 4 hard. $1.30@1.40. Corn-No.\nJ yellow. 80%c; No. 4 yellow. 78%@80c,\nNo 5 yellow, 78%@80c; No 6 yeHow.\n77@77%c; No. 4 mixed, 78@79c; No. 5\nmixed, 77%c; No. 6 mixed 77%c; No. 4\nwhite. 78%@80c; No 5 white. 78c. No.\n6 white, 77%c; sample grade 72@76%c.\nOats No. 2 white, 51@52%c, 3\nwhite. 47%@50%c; No. 4 white, 44@50c;\nsample grade, 43 @49%c. Barley 88c.\nTimothy\u2014s4.3s @5.35. Clover\u2014? 29.2\n36.00.\nChicago Produce\nCHICAGO Butter \u2014Receipts, 9.506;\ncreameries, 39% 40c; standards 40%c;\nfirsts, 36@38c; seconds, 34@35%c; ex\ntras, 41c. Eggs\u2014Receipts, 26,649; ordi\nnaries, 20@21%c; extra firsts, 23%\n24%c; firsts. 22@23c; seconds, 20c; ex\ntras, 25%@26c. Cheese \u2014Twins, 22%c;\nYoung Americas, 23c. Potatoes\u2014Ar\nrivals, old, 49 cars; new, 28; on track,\nold, 193; new, 126; in transit, 440; old\nWisconsin sacked round whites. $2.80\n2 90; Minnesota sacked teobblers, dark,\n52.45; Idaho sacked russets mostly $4.00;\nSprouted, low as $3.75; Alabama sacked\nBliss Triumphs, $3.50 @3.60; Louisiana\nsacked Bliss Triumphs, $3.00 3.2 o.\nSweet potatoes\u2014sl.oo @l.lO. Poultry\u2014\nReceipts, two cars; fowls, heavy, 23c;\nlight, 26%c; roosters, 14c; ducks, 25c;\nspring ducks, 30c; geese, 16c; turkeys No.\n1,25 c; broilers, heavy, 40c; light, 31@\n35c.\nChicago Livestock\nCHICAGO Cattle \u2014Receipts. 10,000;\nfed steers uneven, steady to 15c lower;\nkinds of value, to sell at $11.50@12.50,\nshowing most decline; yearlings, includ\ning yearling heifers, mostly steady;\nother classes steady to strong; fat cows\nscarce, higher in instances; best weighty\nsteers, $13.85; few loads 13.2 5 13.70;\nlargely steer run; better grade western\nfed steers predominating; long yearlings,\nsl2 50; heifer yearlings upward to $11.00;\noutstandingly heavy medium bulls, $7.10;\nlargely $7.00; market on weighty bulls;\nbulk vealers. $10.50@12.50; shippers and\nsmall killers up to 13.00 13.25.\nSheep\u2014Receipts, 10,000; market slow;\ngenerally steady with Tuesday; bulk\ngood to choice Colorado woolskins held\naround $17.25; choice handyweight\nclipped lambs to small killers early\n$16.00; bulk desirable clipped lambs,\n$15.00 @15.75; few clipped culls, $12.00\n12.50; package medium around 40 pounds\nnative spring lambs, $16.50; few desir\nable clipped ewes, $5.00@8.50; few good\nwooled ewes up to $9.50; feeders scarce.\nMilwaukee Livestock\nHOGS\u2014Receipts, 2,000; 10 15c lower.\nPrime heavy and butchers,\n200 lbs. up 9.00@ 9.65\nPrime heavy and butchers,\n200-240 lbs 9.50@10.05\nFair to good lights. 160-190 9.50010.15\nFresh light lights. 130-160.. 9.25@ 9.90\nFair to select packers B.oo@ 5.70\nHairless and rough skinned\nhogs 5.00@ 7.00\nFigs and light lights 8.00 9.00\nStags B.oo@ 8.50\nGovernment throwouts I.oo@ 7.00\nBoars I.oo@ 7.00\nCATTLE \u2014Receipts, 400; steady.\nSteers, good to choice. 9.00@11.00\nMedium to good 8.00 9.00\nFair to medium 7.25@ 8.50\nCommon 5.00@ 7.00\nHelfers, good to choice 7.00@ 8.00\nMedium to good 6.00@ 6.75\nFair to medium 5.50@ 6.00\nCommon to fair 4.50@ 5.00\nCows, good to ch0ice....... 6.25@ 7.00\nMedium to good 5.75 6.25\nFair to medium 5.50@ 5.75\nCutters 4.75@ 5.25\nCanners 4.25@ 4.65\nButchers\u2019 bulls 6.50@ 7.00\nBologna bulls 6.25@ 6.75\nMilkers and springers, good\nto choice (common sell\nfor beef) 60.00@125.00\nCALVES\u2014Receipts, 3,300; steady.\nGood to choice, 100 lbs. up. $11.50 @12.00\nFair to good 10.50@11.25\nThrowouts 6-00\nSHEEP\u2014Receipts. 100; steady.\nGood to choice ewes and\nwether lambs $14.00@16.00\nMedium to good 12.50@14.50\nHeavy bulk lambs 11.00@13.60\nLight ewes 7.50@ 9.00\nCull ewes I.oo@ 4.00\nBucks I.oo@ 4.00\nFOURTEEN\n54,000 Merchants\nIn Chicago, Report\nCHICAGO Chicago has ap\nproximately 54,000 wholesalers, dis\ntributors, jobbers and retailers, ac\ncording to a statement issued yes\nterday by 11. L. Rockhill, who is\ndirecting the work of the federal\ncensus bureau in co-operation with\nthe Chicago Association of Com\nmerce.\nOne-third of the survey is com\npleted, Mr. Rockhill said, approx\nimately 18,000 schedules having\nbeen turned in by enumerators cov\nering the 239 districts into which\nChicago has been divided for the\npurpose of the census. Completion\nof all districts is expected by June\n1 and announcement of results in\nAugust is forecast.\nN. Y. CENTRAL\nSTOCK BOUGHT\nBY VANDERBILT\nNEW YORK Acquirement last\nyear of 21,000 shares of New York\nCentral road stock by H. S. Vander\nbilt is believed to make the Van\nderbilt family the holders of stock\nwith the largest market valuation\nin any individual corporation with\nthe exception of George F. Baker\u2019S\nholdings of First National Bank of\nNew York stock. The acquisition\nof his stock by H. S. Vanderbilt\nbrought his personal holdings of\nCentral stock to 143,000 shares as\ncompared with 139,730 shares held\nby the Baker family at the close of\n1926.\nThe holdings of the Vanderbilt\nfamily at the close of last year to\ntaled 256,532 shares or slightly, more\nthan 6 per cent of the outstanding\nstock. Based on yesterday\u2019s closing\nprice, it has a market value of ap\nproximately $38,000,000. The total\nregistered holdings of the Vander\nbilt family at the close of 1925\namounted to 236,189 shares and at\nthe close of 1924, 193,736 shares.\nThe Oregon Short Line is the larg\nest single stockholder of New York\nCentral, having approximately 227,-\n000 shares.\nCoincident with the fourth anni\nversay of the Baltimore Ohio\u2019s\nCapital Limited train, one of 20 new\npassenger locomotives purchased by\nthe road will be placed on public\nexhibition In Chicago tomorrow.\nThe locomotive, bearing the name\n\u201cPresident Washington,\u201d is painted\ngreen with gold and maroon stripes\nto harmonize with the standard\ntrain color and with the other en\ngines will be used in passenger serv\nice between Washington and New\nYork.\nThe question of dividends on the\ncommon stork of the Texas Pa\ncific railway is a question for the\nboard to decide and as yet no deci\nsion has been reached, W. H. Wil\nliams, chairman of the board of di\nrectors, told the stockholders at the\nannual meeting of stockholders.\n\u201cThe outlook for earnings,\u201d he\nsaid, \u201cdepends largely upon the out\ncome of the flood, the crest of which\nhas not as yet reached our line.\nIf the levees at Big Bend give way,\nit is likely that the larger portion\nof the Louisiana sugar crop will be\ndestroyed. The increase in our\nearnings at present is almost en\ntirely from oil operations.\u201d\nPiggly Wiggly Sales\nRise 100 Per Cent\nPiggly Wiggly Western States\nCo., operating 144 retail grocery\nstores on the Pacific coast, reports\nsales in April of .$1,161,921, com\npared with $579,359 for the same\nmonth in 1926, an increase of 100.6\nper cent.\nNew York Cotton\nNEW YORK \u2014Cotton opened two to\nseven points higher. May 15.32; July\n15.52; October 15.84; January 16,08;\nMarch 16.25.\nMilwaukee Produce Prices\u2014Corrected Daily\nB _ n\u2014H\u2014\nDAIRY MARKETS.\nButter\u2014 Creamery, fresh, extras, tubs,\n41c; extra firsts, 40@40%c; firsts, 38@\n39c; seconds, 35@37c; centralized, 88 to\n89 score, 40c; ladles, 36 @3Bc; Packing\nstock No. 1, 26@28c; off-stock, 15@20c.\nCheese American, full cream, twins,\n22%@23c; daisies, single, 23@23%c;\ndouble, 23@23%c; Young Americas, 23\n23 %c; longhorns, 23%@24c; squares,\n23%@24c. 5-lb. loaves \u2014American, 31@\n33c; pimento, 34@36c; brick, 32@34c;\nSwiss, 38 41c. Special makes \u2014Brick,\nfancy, 21%@22c; limburger, fall make,\n22% @23c; winter make, 19%@-0c;\nSwiss, block, 26@29c; loaf, 30@36c; Im\nported. Swiss, 42 45c.\nEggs\u2014Fresh-gathered firsts, standard\ncases included,, 21%@22%c; ordinary\nfirsts, shippers\u2019 cases included. 2G%@ 21c;\nstorage packed. 25@25%c; dirties, can\ndied, 19%@20c; seconds, checks, can\ndied, 18% 19c.\nMEATS AND POULTRY.\nPigeons Old flyers, live, per doz.,\n$2.00@2.25; dead, $1.50; squabs, live, per\ndoz., $2.00@2.50; dressed, fat, $3.00@\n3.50; thin, poorly dressed. SI.OO @1.50.\nPoultry\u2014Live\u2014Fowls, general run,\n26c; leghorns. 25c; roosters, old or staggy\nvou\u2019ng 14%c; broilers, 2 lbs. and over,\n42c- 1% to 2 lb^. 40c; leghorns, 2 lbs.\nand up, 35c; turkeys, plump, 28c; ducks,\n28c; geese, 16c; Guinea liens, per doz.,\nold.\u2019 $5.00; young. $6.00.\nVeal\u2014Calves, 50 to 60 lbs., fair kid\nneys. ll@12c; 60 to 70 lbs., choice,\nmeaty. 13@14c; 70 to 80 lbs., good kid\nneys, 14@15c; 80 to 90 lbs., choice, 15\n16c- 90 to 110 lbs., fancy, bright, 16\n17c; extra fancy. 18c; thin, bony, poor\nkidneys, poorly dressed or off-stock, 80\nto 175 lbs., as to quality and condition,\n9@lle.\nHides\u2014calf, green. 17c; cured. 18c;\nkips, green, 12c; cured, 13c; cow, green,\n7c; cured. 8c; bull, green, sc; cured, 6c;\ndeacons, green, each, 60c; slunk, green,\neach 25c; horse No. 1. green, each, $3.50;\ndo. No. 2 green, each. $2.25; pelts, green,\neach. 50c@51.50.\nFRUITS.\nApples\u2014Eastern, bushel, $1.25 @1.50;\nbarrels. $3.00@4.00; 'Western. boxes. De\nlicious. $3.50@3.75; W\u2019ine Saps. $2.75@\n3.00.\nBananas \u2014Per 100 ibs.. $6.00@7.00.\nCherries \u2014California, boxes, 13 row,\n$5.00@5.50.\nGrapes\u2014Almerias, 20 ib. boxes, $5.00\n6.00.\nThe Leader Financial Page\nHARAHAN SEES\nWEST HUB IN\nERIE MERGER\nWA SHINGTON Chicago\u2019s im\nportance as a coal market and\ngateway to the west and northwest\nwas emphasized today by W. J.\nHarahan, president of the Chesa\npeake Ohio, in testimony before\nthe interstate commerce commission\nin support of the revised Van Swer\ningen rail merger plan.\nTo Cost $34,000,000.\nMr. Harahan said the line of the\nErie from Marion, 0., to Chicago\nwould furnish, in connection with\nthe Hocking Valley and the Chesa\npeake Ohio from Russell, Ky., the\nassembling yard for west bound coal\nof the C. 0., a superior line to\nChicago for the transportation of\ncoal, as compared with the C.\nO.\u2019s existing line through Cincin\nnati.\nTo improve the existing line\nwould cost around $34,000,000, he\nsaid, while the C. O. could buy\ncontrol of the Erie for $42,042,573,\nor only about $8,000,000 more than\nthe cost of obtaining what he said\nwould be an inferior line from Cin\ncinnati to Chicago. In addition, he\nsaid, the Erie would return a sub\nstantial return bn the investment\nmade in it.\n\u201cThere is no other line in exist\nence which will equal the Chesa\npeake Ohio-Hocking Valley-Erie\nline and no better line can be con\nstructed between the coal fields and\nChicago, considering grade and\neconomy of service,\u201d he said.\n\u201cThe line into Chicago from the\ncoal fields is a particularly impor\ntant one for the public and the\nChesapeake Ohio, because Chi\ncago is a large consuming point for\ncoal, consuming about 36,000,000\ntons per annum, of wich the Chesa\npeake Ohio furnished via all rail\n4,472,655 tons in 1926. Chicago is,\nin addition, the great gateway for\nthe west and northwest.\u201d\nYellow Truck, Coach\nCHICAGO \u2014The first quarter of\nthis year was one of the poorest\nperiods in the history of the Yellow\nTruck Coach Co. For the three\nmonths ended March 31 the com\npany incurred a net loss of $668,-\n190, after depreciation, etc.\nAs payment of the quarterly div\nidend on the $15,000,000 preferred\nstock required $262,500, the total\ndeficit for the quarter would be\n$930,690. Total surplus on Dec. 31,\n1926, was $8,073,770. Net sales for\nthe quarter were $7,708,658.\nThe quarter\u2019s loss before divi\ndends compared with net profit of\n$485,520 in the first quarter of\n1926.\nFloods Cut Crop\nAcreage in Illinois\nSurvey Reports\nSPRlNGFlELD\u2014Abandonment of\nconsiderable crop acreage in south\nIllinois and retarding of field work\nin the same area due to the unprec\nedented floods, is reported in the\nweekly crop bulletin of the United\nStates weather bureau published\ntoday.\nThe survey states, however, that\nfair to good progress was made in\ncentral and northern counties of\nIllinois until halted by the heavy\nrains of Saturday, Sunday and\nMonday. Little corn has been\nplanted, and oats are doing well\ngenerally in the north, central and\nin some southern counties, the sur\nvey adds.\nDuring the week a little cotton\nwas planted on high ground in the\nsouth, while progress of wheat was\ngood in north and central districts\nbut unsatisfactory in the south.\nStrawberries from the south are on\nthe market and apple trees are in\nfull bloom in the north, the report\nconcludes.\nLemons \u2014California, per box, $4.50\n5.00.\nLimes\u2014lmported, 100, $2.00@2.25.\nOranges California, new Navels, per\nbox, as to size and quality, $5.50@6.00;\nValencias, 5.25 5.7 5; Florida, $5.00@\n5.50; Indian Rivers, $5.50@6.00.\nTangerines\u2014California, boxes, $2.75\n@3.00.\nPears \u2014Western, boxes, Winter Welles,\n$5.50@6.00.\nPineapples\u2014Cuban, crate, $5.00 @5.50.\nMELONS.\nCantaloupes Calif., crate, SIO.OO\n12.00.\nBERRIES.\nStrawberries \u2014Tennessee, 24 qt. cases,\n$3.00@3.50; Arkansas,, $3.50@4.25; Mis\nsouri, $3.50 @4.00.\nVEGETABLES.\nAsparagus\u2014lllinois, boxes, 20 bunches,\n$1.00@L25; sections, 24 bunches, $1.25@\n1.50; Ashton, $1.75@2.00; home-grown,\ndoz. bunches, 75c@51.00.\nAvacadoes \u2014Calif., doz., $5.00 @B.OO.\nBeets New, Texas, bushels, $1.75\n2,00; California, crate, $4.25@4.50; Mis\nsissippi. hampers, $1.50 @1.75.\nCabbage\u2014New, southern, crate, $6.50\n@7.00.\nCarrots \u2014New, Texas, bushels, $2.00\n2.25; Mississippi, hampers, $1.50@1.75.\nCauliflower\u2014California, crate, $2.75\n3.00.\nCelery California, crate, $5.50@7.00;\nFlorida, $4.50@5.00.\nCelery Root\u2014Home-grown, doz., as to\nsize, 25@60c.\nCucumbers\u2014Hot house, boxes. 2 doz.,\n$3.00@3.50; Texas, bushels, $3.00@3.50.\nEgg Plant\u2014Florida, crate, $5.00@5.50.\nGarlic\u2014California, per lb., 6@Bc.\nGreen Peas\u2014California, crates, $5.00@\n6.00; hampers, $3.75@4.00.\nHorseraaisn southern, root, per lb.,\nfancy, thick, B@loc.\nLeek Home-grown, per bunch, 13\nstalks, large, 40c; small, 25@30c.\nLettuce Leaf Home-grown, hot\nhouse, doz. bunches, 65@75c.\nLettuce \u2014Head\u2014lceberg, fancy. West\nern $5.00@5.50; off-stock, $2.50@3.50.\nMushrooms\u2014Per lb.. No. 1, 1-lb. boxes,\n70@75c; buttons, 60@65c.\nOnions \u2014Yellow, sacks, per 100 lbs..\nWestern. $4.50@5.00; new. Texas, crate,\nyellow. $3.00@3.25; white, $3.50@3.75;\nSpanish, per crate, $2.00@2.25; Valencias,\ncrate, $3.25@3.50.\nOyster Plant \u2014Fer doz. bunches, SI.OO\n@l.lO.\nLine Is Important.\nCo. Shows Loss\nMILWAUKEE, THURSDAY, MAY 12, 1927\nHardwood Lumber\nMart Unsettled\nIn Memphis Area\nMEMPHlS\u2014Unsettled conditions\nprevail in the hardwood lumber in\ndustry in this district. Many of the\noperators whose mills are dowm be\ncause of the flood have taken their\nlumber off the market and are not\nquoting prices on oak, gumwood,\npoplar or other woods.\nThere is a wide range in such\nprices as are quoted, particularly\non gum and it looks as if there will\nbe a runaway market on that\nspecies with oak and poplar fol\nlowing to a certain extent.\nIn some districts the poplar\nmanufacturers also have with\ndrawn from the market and are\nadvising all representatives not to\nsell without first taking up price\noffers with the mill.\nOIL INDUSTRY\nSEEKS HELP\nWASHINGTON\u2014Leading oil pro\nducers have appealed to the govern\nment to aid in restricting oil out\nput, and the federal oil board has\nreplied that the government is ready\nto assist any proper manner.\nThe appeal, which embodies a re\nstriction plan to guard against over\nproduction, was addressed to Secre\ntary Work, chairman of the oil\nboard, and was signed by Walter C.\nTeagle, president of the Standard\nOil Co. of New Jersey, and W. S.\nFarish, former president of the\nAmerican Petroleum institute.\nIt declared that overproduction\nhad \u201crecurred this year in a form\nso malignant as to seem to be with\nout precedent.\u201d A co-operative\nmethod of control, worked out\nthrough joint purchase of certain\nproducing lands, was proposed as a\nsolution.\nBRIGGS CO. BOOMING.\nDETROlT\u2014Substantial additions\nto the automobile body business of\nthe Briggs Manufacturing Co., in\nthe acquisition of Dodge and Chrys\nler as customers in 1926, was dis\nclosed at the annual meeting of\nstockholders here today. All di\nrectors of the company were re\nelected.\nCOAL USE CITED.\nCHlCAGO\u2014Twentyfive to 28 per\ncent of the annual coal production\nof the United States is consumed by\nthe railroads, speakers said at the\nInternational Railway Fuel Assn,\nconvention at the Hotel Sherman\nyesterday.\nGrain Futures\nWHEAT.\nPrevious\nHigh. Low. Close. Close.\nMay 1.42% 1.41 1.41% 1.42\nJuly 1.35% 1.34 1.34% 1.35%\nSept 1.32% 1.31% 1.32% 1.32%\nCORN.\nPrevious\nHigh. Low. Close. Close.\nMay 81% 79% 81% 79%\nJuly 86% 83% 86% 84%\nSept 89% 86% 89% 87%\nOATS.\nPrevious\nHigh. Low. Close. Close.\nMay 48% 48% 48% 48%\nJuly 49% 48% 49% 48%\nSept 46% 45% 46% 45%\nRYE.\nPrevious\nHigh. Low. Close. Close.\nMay 1.08% 1.08% 1.08% 1.08%\nJuly 1.06% 1.05% 1.06% 1.06%\nSept 99% 98% 99% 98%\nCash Grain\nBarley.\nStrong and again 1c higher. Receipts\nfair but mostly on sale. Good malting\ndemand with daily sales of to arrive\nlots. Choice to fancy, 48 to 50 lb. test,\nquotable at 95@96c; fair to good, 44 to\n47 lb. test, 90@95c; lightweight, 40 to 43\nlb. test, 85@92c; feed, 75@85c.\nCorn\nFirm and wanted with futures. Re\nceipts light. Fresh shelled in good de\nmand, No. 4 yellow and white quotable\n6@Bc under July. No. 4 mixed, B@loc\nunder July, as to moisture and color.\nOats\nUnchanged with futures. Receipts\nmoderate. Good demand for heavy;\nslow for poor. No. 3 white quotable\nMay price to 3c over.\nRye\nEasier and 1c lower with futures. Re\nceipts light. Shippers buying. No. 2\nquotable at $1.08@1.09, ranging at 1c\nunder to May. Heavy discounts prevail\nfor wet parcels and out of condition.\nWheat\nSteady and unchanged with futures.\nParsley Home-grown, dozen small\nlunches 25@30c.\nParsnips Home-grown, bu.. washed,\n$1.15@1.25; unwashed, 65@75c.\nPeppers\u2014Florida, crates, $4.50 @5.50.\nPieplant\u2014Home-grown, doz. bunches,\n35@40c.\nPotatoes Minnesota, Michigan, Wis\nconsin, sacks, 100 lbs., white stock, on\ntrack, $2.65@2.75; western, russets, $4.00\n@4.25.\nPotatoes New\u2014Florida, bbls., Hast\nings, $8.00@8.25; Texas, red. per 100\nlbs., $4.00@4.25.\nRadishes Home-grown, doz. bchs.,\nhotbed, 65@75c.\nRutabagas Canadian, per 100 lbs.,\n$3.50@4.00.\nShallots \u2014Louisiana, bbls., $6.00@8.00.\nSpinach\u2014St. Louis, per bushel, $1.40@\n1.50; Baltimore, $1.50@1.75; California,\ncrate, $4.25@4.50.\nString Beans Louisiana, hampers,\nwax or green, $2.00@2.50.\nTomatoes California, repacked, 6-\nbasket crates, $5.00@5.50; lugs, $2.00\n3.00.\nSweet Potatoes Tennessee, hampers,\nNancy Halls, $1.50@1.75; Indiana, bu.,\n$2.00@2.25.\nTurnips\u2014New, Texas, bushel, $1.50\n2.00; Louisiana, bbls., $5.00@5.50.\nWatercress \u2014Wisconsin, per bbl., $4.00\n@5.00.\nPRODUCE MARKETS.\nBeans Navies, choice, hand picked,\nper 100 lbs. (sacks included), $4.00@\n4.50; Red Kidney. $7.00@7.50; Brown\nSwedish, $6.00@6.50; Lima Beans, Cali\nfornia, $7.50@8.00.\nBees Wax Choice to fancy, per lb.,\nbright, 2S@3oc; dark. 23@25c, and\ndown to 20c.\nHoney Comb, per cases, 25 1-lb. sec\ntions, fancy, white, $4.75@5.00; dark,\n$4.25@4.50; mixed sells at around $4.25.\nExtracted, lb., white clover, ll@12c;\namber, 9@loc.\nPeas\u2014Per 100 lbs. (new, 100-lb. sacks),\ngreen, $3.00; Scotch, $3.25; white, $4.25;\nmarrow fats, $5.00; split peas, yellow,\n$5.75@6.00; green, $5.75@6.00.\nPop Corn\u2014Quotable per 100 lbs., ears.\n$3 00@3.50; shelled. do. $4.00@5.00:\nbroken, poor. less.\nTallow\u2014Prime, 9%@10c; No. 1, solid,\n6%@7c; No. 2, 5%@6c; cakes, 7%@Bc;\nrough, 2%@3c.\nWool\u2014Medium, per lb., 30@32c; low,\n38@3\u00bbe.\nWestern Railroads\nAttain Prosperity\nNEW YORK \u2014Western railroads\nare rolling in prosperity, according\nto the annual reports which just\nnow circulated in Wall Street.\nThe Union Pacific has made pub\nlic its report for the year ending\nDec. 31, 1926. It covers not only\nthe Union Pacific proper, but the\nOregon Short line, the Oregon-\nWashington Railroad Navigation\nCo. and the Los Angeles Salt\nLake.\nThe gross income for 1926 was\n$205,416,263; expenses totaled $140,-\n769,540; taxes amounted to $15,-\n739,884.\nTo the net income must be added\nthe income from the company\u2019s out\nside investments, which totaled\n$17,129,663, and its income from\nmiscellaneous sources totaling sl,-\n371,231.\nEarns $16.64 Share.\nAfter deducting equipment ren\ntals and interest on bonds, the com\npany had a balance of $40,984,749.\nOf this sum the preferred stock\nreceived in dividends $3,981,740,\nwhile the dividends on the common\namounted to $22,229,160.\nAfter putting a small sum in the\nFAIRBANKS NET\nSHOWS DECLINE\nCHICAGO \u2014Decline in the busi-\nness of Fairbanks, Morse Co.,\nwhich developed in the latter part\nof 1926 on account of the business\nrecession in the southern part of the\ncountry, continued through the first\nquarter of 1927.\nThis is reflected in the company\u2019s\nearnings statement for the three\nmonths ending March 31, which\nshows that the net income, after\nall charges, amounted to $100,087,\nas compared with $525,012 in the\ncorresponding period of 1926;\nThese earnings are equal to $1.36\na share on the 73,389 share of pre\nferred stock and compare with $1.07\na share earned on the 368,977 shares\nof common stock last year. After\nthe payment of dividends on the\npreferred and common stocks for\nthe first quarter, there was a deficit\nof $303,576, as compared with a\nsurplus of $116,652 last year.\nHearing on Steel\nFreight Rates Gets\nUnder Way Today\nCHICAGO \u2014The interstate com\nmerce commission held hearings at\nthe Edgewater Beach hotel today\non iron and steel freight rates. The\nhearings are the outgrowth of the\nHoch-Smith resolution calling for a\ngeneral investigation of iron and\nsteel freight rates from the Atlan\ntic seaboard to the Mississippi river\nand north of the Ohio river.\nThe Chicago hearing is the fourth\nconducted by the commerce commis\nsion. Previous sessions have been\nheld at Pittsburgh, Columbus and\nDetroit.\nThe commerce commission inves\ntigation is the result of efforts on\nthe part of agricultural interests to\nobtain lower freight rates. This re\nsulted in the Hoch-Smith resolution\ncalling for a general investigation\nof iron and steel freight rates.\n|n.Y, Stock Market Closing Prices|\nWednesday\nClose.\nAllied Chemical 138%\nAllis-Chalmers 107%\nAmerican Can 48%\nAmerican Car and Foundry..\u201elo3%\nAmerican and Foreign P0w.... 21%\nAmerican Locomotive 109%\nAmerican Smelt, and Ref 148%\nAmerican Sugar Refining 89%\nAmerican Tel. and Tel 165%\nAmerican Tobacco B 130\nAmerican Woolen\nAnaconda Copper 45%\nA. T. and S. F 180\nBaldwin Loco 189%\nB. and 0 122%\nBethlehem Steel 50%\nCalif Pkg 66%\nCalif. Pet 23%\nCan. Pac 179%\nCase (J. I.) Thresh. Mach\u2014l\u00df6_\nCentral Leather 10%\nCerro de Pasco Copper 61%\nChes, and Ohio 174\nChicago Great West 18%\nC. M. and St. P 15\nC. M. and St. P. pfd 24%\nChicago and Northwestern 87%\nChicago R. I. and Pac 99%\nChile Copper 36%\nChrysler Motors 45%\nColo. Fuel and Iron 87%\nCons. Gas 100%\nCorn Prod, Ref 59%\nCruc. Steel 86%\nDupont de Nemours 241\nElectric Power and Light ctfs 20%\nErie Railroad 54%\nGeneral Asphalt 75%\nGeneral Cigar Co 58\nGeneral Electric 97%\nGeneral Motors 194\nGoodrich, B. F., 55%\nGreat Northern pfd 88%\nGreat Northern Ore ctfs 19%\nGreene Cananea 47%\nHudson Motors 86%\nIllinois Central 126%\nLndian Refining 9\nInspiration Copper 17%\nInternational Harvester 167\nInternal. Merc. Marine 7%\nInternational Paper 51\nKansas City Southern 58%\nKansas City Southern pfd 69%\nKenecott Copper 64%\nsinking fund, the company had a\nsurplus of $14,768,172.\nStated in another way, after\nthe company had paid all its ex\npenses, including taxes, interest\nupon its bonds and preferred stock,\nit had available for dividends on\nthe common stock $16.64 a share.\nWall Street is accustomed to\nenormous profits, but even W all\nStreet opens its eyes when a public\nutility corporation earns 16.64 per\ncent on the par value of its common\nstock.\nThe report reveals the great\nwealth of the Union Pacific. It has\nin cash $38,972,343. It has invest\nments in outside corporations of\n$159,889,554,and it has tucked away\nin its \u201cstrong box\u201d government se\ncurities valued at $31,999,544.\nPacific Not Alone.\nThe Union Pacific does not stand\nalone by any means.\nFor example, the Rock Island an\nnounces that in March it doubled its\nnet operating income, or profit, as\ncompared with the same month last\nyear. The gross revenues of the\nroad went up $1,696,000, but the\nprofits totaled $2,128,212, as com\npared with $1,000,222 in March,\n1926. The Rock Island\u2019s surplus for\nthe first three months of this year\nwas $2,109,152, as contrasted with a\ndeficit of $110,579 for the cor\nresponding quarter of 1926.\nThe first 70 class 1 railroads to\nreport for March announced that\ntheir profits were $88,949,000, as\ncompared with $88,974,000 in March\nof last year, the latter being consid\nered an exceptionally fine showing.\nNew York Produce\nNEW YORK \u2014Flour, dull and unset\ntled. Pork, dull; mess, $36.00. Lard,\neasy; midwest spot, $12.70@12.80. Sugar,\nraw, firm; spot, 96 test, delivered duty\npaid $4.83; refined, quiet; granulated,\n$6.00@6.20. Coffee, Rio No. 7 on spot,\n15%@15%c; Santos No. 4, 17@17%c.\nTallow, dull; special to extra 7%\n7%c. Hay, firm; No. 1, $L30@1.35, No,\n3, $1.10@1.20; clover, $1.10@1.25. Dressed\npoultry, Irregular; turkeys, 25 46c;\nchickens, 20@42c; broilers, 2a@ 50c;ca\npons, 30@46c; fowls, 14@34c; ducks, 20\n@23c; ducks, Long Islands, 24c. Live\npoultry, steady; geese, 10@15c; ducks\n12@27c; fowls, 25@28c; turkeys,. 20@23c,\nroosters. 16c; capons, 35c; broilers, 20\n@soc. Cheese, steady; state whole milk,\nfancy to specials, 27 28c; Young Amer\nicas 25%@28c. Potatoes, Long Islands,\n$5.00@5.25; southern, $3.50@6.50; Maine,\n$4 60@5.75; Bermuda, $3.50@8.00. Sweet\npotatoes. Jersey, basket, 50c @52.50;\nsouthern, basket, $1.25@1.70. Butter,\neasier; receipts, 14,775; creamery extras,\n43%@43%c; special market, 44@44,^c.\nEggs, weak; receipts, 44,466; nearby\n^hite fancy, 31 33c; nearby state\nwhites, 25 30c; fresh firsts. 23% 25c,\nPacific coasts, 28@35c; western whites,\n25@28c; nearby browns, 29@32c.\nPRIMARY GRAIN MOVEMENT.\nPrimary car receipts today follow:\nWht. Corn Oats Barley Rye\nMilwaukee. 5 3 20 21 2\nChicago 27 30 33 6\nMinneapolis 147 5 1- 7 6\nDuluth 104 9 12\nWinnipeg 266 120 14 16\nKansas City 57 13\nSt. Louis 22 34 31\nOmaha 21 25 4\nWichita 30\nMILWAUKEE FT.OTJR AND SEEDS.\nClover Seed \u2014Red, per 100 lbs., choice\nto fancy, $32.00 @36.00; country lots,\n$25.00@30.00; dirty, $21.00@25.00; alsike,\n$27.00@34.00; white, $20.00@30.00. Mixed\nlower.\nTimothy Seed Quotable $4.50@5.00;\naccording to quality for country lots;\nfancy, $5.25.\nFlaxseed Basis Minneapolis freight\nNo. 1 N. W. $2.29 @2.39; bag lots dis\ncounted s@lsc.\nFlour Straight, $7.10@7.25; patent,\n$7.25@7.50; clear, $6.00@6.50. Rye\u2014\nStraight, $5.90@6.15; patent, $6.05@6.25;\ndark, $5.25@5.45.\nMillstuffs \u2014Sacked bran. $30.50 31.00;\nstandard middlings, $30.00 @30.50; flour\nmiddlings, $33.00 34.00; oil meal. $50.00\n@51.00, 100-lb. sacks. Gluten feed, $31.40.\nBeans Navy\u2014Bag lots, $4.50 @5.00\nper 100-lb. sacks.\nPopcorn\u2014Per 100 lbs., $2.50@3.00.\nBuckwheat \u2014Silver hull, per 100 lbs.,\n$2.00 @2.15; Japanese, $2.10 @2.20, sub\nject to dockage.\nSpeltz\u2014Per 100 lbs., $1,15@1.25.\nWednesday\nClose.\nKresge, S. S 51%\nLehigh Valley 122%\nLouisville and Nashville 139%\nMarland Oil 38\nMiami Copper 15%\nMissouri, Kansas and Texas.... 47%\nMissouri Pacific 55%\nMontgomery Ward 64%\nNational Biscuit 131%\nNational Lead 196%\nNevada Consolidated Copper.. 14%\nNew York Central 148%\nN. Y. N. H. and H 49\nNorthern Pacific 87%\nPacific Gas and Electric 37\nPacific Oil 1%\nPan-American Petroleum 58%\nPennsylvania Railroad 61%\nPeoples Gas (Chicago) 140%\nPure Oil 27%\nReading 115%\nReplogle Steel 10%\nRepublic Iron and Steel 65%\nRoyal Dutch 50%\nSears,Roebuck 54\nShell Union Oil 28%\nSinclair Consolidated 17%\nSouthern Pacific 113\nSouthern Railroad 125%\nStandard Oil of California 55%\nStandard- Oil of New Jersey.... 36%\nStudebaker 53%\nTennessee Copper 9%\nTexas and Pacific 80%\nTimken Bearing 91%\nTobacco Products 100%\nTranscontinental Oil 4\nUnion Oil of California 44\nUnion Pacific 174%\nUnited States Rubber 53%\nUnited States Steel 170%\nUnited States Steel pfd ....131\nVanadium 47\nVir. Carolina Chemical 7%\nWabash 68\nWabash pfd A 95\nWestern Union 162\nWestinghouse E. and M 73%\nWillys Overland 21%\nYellow Truck and Coach 27%\nReynolds Tobacco B 123\nPAGE FOURTEEN\nI. C. C. Refuses to\nCut Grain Rates\nCHICAGO Proposals of the\nMinneapolis St. Louis and Soo\nLine roads for a 6-cent reduction\nper 100 pounds on grain rates from\nMinneapolis territory to the eastern\nseaboard, was refused by the inter\nstate commerce commission at Wash\nington yesterday.\nThe carriers proposed the reduc\ntion last summer, the commission\ndeclining to accept it after hearings\nhad been conducted.\nPetition for reconsideration was\nfiled by railroads concerned and\ngrain interests of the midwest. Yes\nterday\u2019s ruling of the commission\ncloses the case.\nWHEAT MART\nNEEDS SUPPORT\nAS PIT OPENS\nCHICAGO\u2014With the trade senti\nment less pronounced on the bull\nside of wheat after yesterday\u2019s eve\nning up process and with Liverpool\nabout as expected, opening quota\ntions on the Chicago Board of Trade\nwere %c higher to %c lower, than\nWednesday\u2019s close.\nWeather conditions were some\nwhat more favorable, and should\nthe improvement continue, leaders\nbelieve the market will need con\nstant support, to keep from going\nlower. There is now considerable\nshort interest in the market, how\never, and revival of export buying\non a large scale might offset all\nother considerations.\nAfter yesterday\u2019s sharp advance,\nand with weather favorable to corn\nplanting, prices inay be partially\nerased today. Prices opened to\n%c lower than the previous close.\nBulls on corn are watching weather\nconditions closely and one of the\nmost pronounced of the local bull\nelement said he expected- corn to\nhave setbacks from time to time,\nbut eventually to sell much higher.\nOats are displaying considerable\nstrength, but trade continues nar\nrow. Opening prices were un\nchanged to %c higher than yester\nday\u2019s close. Nearly all commission\nhouses are advocating purchases of\nJuly oats, and this may attract new\ninvestment buying of sufficient\nvolume to add much to present\nvalues.\nProvisions opened steady.\nWheat\u2014May, up %c; July, off\n%c September, off %c.\nCorn\u2014May, off %c; July, off %c;\nSeptember, off %c.\nCorn\u2014May, off %c; July, ^c;\nSeptember, off %c.\nOats\u2014May, unchanged; July, up\n%c; September, unchanged.\nMILWAUKEE CAR RECEIPTS.\nMil. N. W. Soo Total\nWheat 1 3 4\nCorn 1 2 3\nOats 4 16 20\nBarley 2 18 1 21\nRyo 1 1 2\nTotals 9 40 1 50\nNEW YORK STOCKS.\nElectric Boat 18%\nFisk Rubber 17^\nGeneral Outdoor Advertising.. 43\nHupp 21%\nInternational Nickel 57%\nMo. Kans., and Tex.,-,pfd 103%\nMissouri Pacific, pfd 107%\nMack Truck 114%\nNorth American 48\nNash Motor 03%\nPackard Motor 36\nR. J. Reynolds B 123\nWoolworth 140%\nMidwest Utilities 108\nSub Boat 7%\nTexas Corporation 47%\nConsider the House\nBehind the Bonds\nan INVESTMENT is seldom\nbetter than the house behind it,\nand the investment house is never\nbetter than the bonds it issues.\nThe Service rendered by the House\nof Schroeder has built the good will\nthat is so much cherished by this\nhouse.\nThe purchase of a First Mortgage\nReal Estate Bond sponsored by the\nHouse of Schroeder is an exercise\nof good judgment because both the\nhouse and the issue will successful\nly meet the most exacting standards.\nChris. Schroeder Son Co.,\n__ _ 86 E. Michigan St., Milwaukee, Wis.\nClip and I Please send me literature on conserva' I\n.1 m the investments.\nMail This\nNow Name\nAddress\nL\nChris. Schroeder Son Co.\n86 E. Michigan St. Phone Broadway 1951\nMilwaukee, Wis.\n\u201c38 Years Without Loss to Any Investor'*\nWednesday\u2019s Grain Changes\nBarley\u2014Active; 1c higher.\nCorn\u2014Firm.\nOats \u2014Unchanged.\nRye\u2014lc lower.\nWheat\u2014Unchanged.\nSTEEL JUMPS\nUP AND DOWN;\nOILS FLUTTER\nNEW YORK\u2014The irregularity\nbrought on by Profit-taking toward\nthe close of the stock market yester\nday carried over in today's early*\ndealings. Changes, however, werej\nnot wide on the downside, and lead\ning issues continued to show a firm;\nundertone.\nU. S. Steel opened at 170%, up\nbut later declined to its previous\nclosing level. The new \u201cwhen is\nsued\u201d stock opened at 122, off\nand held at the figure for several\nearly transactions. General Motors\nsagged off point to 193%, having\npreviously reached 194.\nOther motor shares were mixed\nwith Hudson up at 86%, Chrysler\nup at 45%, Mack Truck off\nat 113% and Willys-Overland off\nat 20%.\nConstructive operations seemed\nin the ascendancy today following\nthe reaction due to profit-taking late\nin the session yesterday.\nNews development overnight with\na bearing on the stock market were\nnot important and trading was light\nin early dealings.\nOil shares displayed a greatly im\nproved tone responding to the be\nlief that producers were generally\nfinally awakening to the seriousness\nof the overproduction situation and\nwere showing signs of willingness tc\nco-operate regarding curtailment,\nPhillips Petroleum spurted td\n44% on transactions aggregating 4.-\n000 shares, while Marland stiffened\nto 38%.\nNickel Plate was a strong spot In\nfurther response to expectation that\na majority of the 900,000 shares oj\nnew Chesapeake corporation will\nbe distributed to Nickel Plate share\nholders. i\nOpening prices included:\nGeneral Motors 193%, off\nMack Truck 113%, off Willys-\nOverland 20%, off New York\nCentral 148%, off Atchison\n179%, off International Nickel\n57%, off U. S. Steel when issued\n122, off Southern R. R. 125, off\nColorado Fuel 87%; General\nElectric 97%, up Phillips Petro\nleum 44%, up Erie 55, up\nU. S. Steel 170%, up New Haven\n49; Missouri Pacific 56%, up\nAmerican Smelting 149. up\nBaldwin 189%, off Baltimore <S(\nOhio 122%, up\nMILWAUKEE HAY MARKET.\nNo. 1 timothy, SIB.OO @19.00; No. 5\ntimothy, $16.00 @18.00; No. 3 timothy,\nsl\u00df.oo@ 16.00; No. 1 mixed, $18.00; No. 3\nclover mixed, $16.00; sample hay, SIO.OO\n@13.00; marsh feeding, $11.00@12.001\npacking, SIO.OO @10.50; rye. straw, SIO.OO\n@10.50; oat straw, $10.00@10.50.\nChicago Grain Range\nJames E. Bennett Co.\nPrevious\nWheat\u2014High. low. Close. Close.\nMay 1.42% 1.40% 1.41% 1.41%\nJuly 1.35% 1.34% 1.35 1.35%\nSept 1.33 1.31% 1.32% 1.32%\nCorn\u2014\u2022\nMay 82 78% 81% 79\nJuly 87 83% 86% 84\nSept 89% 86% 89% 87%\nOats\nMay 49% 48% 48% 48%\nJuly 49% 48% 49% 48%\nSept 46% 45% 46% 45%\nLard\u2014\nJuly 12.30 12.22 12.25 12.30\nSept 12.52 12.45 12.45 12.50\nRibs\u2014\nMay 13.00 13.00\nRye-\nMay 1.09% 1.08% 1.08% 1.09\nJuly 1.06% 1.05% 1.06% 1.06%\nSept 99% 98% 99% 98%\nNORTHWESTERN MARKETS.\nMINNEAPOLIS\u2014Wheat, May, $1.39;\nJuly, $1.40%; September, $1.36%\n1.36%. Oats, May, 47%c; July, 47%e;\nSeptember, 44%c. Barley, May, 86c;\nJuly, 83c, Rye, May, $1.03; July, SIOO%.\nFlax, May, $2.25%; July, $1.00%. Flax,\nMay, $2.25% July, $2.30%.\nWINNIPEG Wheat, May, $1.51%;\nJuly, $1.47%; October, $1.34% @1.35.","height":"29244","width":"21660"}}
